===============================================================================
GMATWiz - GMAT Quantitative Reasoning (Problem Solving) CONTENT PIPELINE
===============================================================================
Location : anki-fork/gmatwiz/content/
Generated: 2026-06-30 (UTC)
Scope    : GMAT Focus Edition -> Quantitative Reasoning -> Problem Solving ONLY.
           Arithmetic + Algebra. NO geometry. NO Data Sufficiency. (PRD Section 5)

This directory is SELF-CONTAINED and ADDITIVE. It creates files ONLY under
gmatwiz/content/ and does not modify, move, or delete anything elsewhere in the
Anki fork.


-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
1. WHAT IS HERE (files + exact paths)
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
anki-fork/gmatwiz/content/
  taxonomy.py        Shared module: the PRD Section 5 leaf-topic taxonomy, the
                     JSON schema + validator, a keyword TOPIC TAGGER, a geometry/
                     data-sufficiency out-of-scope filter, a difficulty
                     heuristic, and dedup helpers. Imported by the two scripts.
  scraper.py         Reusable scraper. Pulls free/public GMAT Quant PS questions,
                     respects robots.txt, normalizes to the schema, dedupes
                     (exact + near-duplicate), auto-tags topics, writes raw
                     captures + questions.json + scrape_report.json.
  make_seed.py       Authors the original SEED set and SELF-VERIFIES every item
                     (recomputes each answer in code), then writes seed.json.
                     The build fails loudly if any question's math is wrong.

  questions.json     OUTPUT: scraped + normalized questions (231 items).
  seed.json          OUTPUT: 42 original, independently-verified questions.
  scrape_report.json OUTPUT: machine-readable per-source run report.
  README             This file.

  raw/               Raw per-source captures (provenance), e.g.:
    aqua_rat__dataset__<ts>.jsonl   raw AQuA-RAT JSON-lines as fetched
    gmatclub__robots__<ts>.txt      the robots.txt decision for GMAT Club
    reddit__robots__<ts>.txt        Reddit's robots.txt (Disallow: /)

  __pycache__/       Python bytecode cache (safe to delete).


-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
2. NORMALIZED JSON SCHEMA (one object per question)
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Every item in BOTH questions.json and seed.json has exactly these fields, in
this order:

  {
    "id":          string  - "<source>-<12 hex>" content hash (stable, unique)
    "stem":        string  - the question text
    "options":     object  - {"A","B","C","D","E"} -> non-empty strings
    "correct":     string  - one of "A".."E"
    "explanation": string  - worked solution / rationale (may be "" if a source
                             provided none; always present for seed.json)
    "topic":       string  - exactly one leaf, e.g. "gmat::quant::algebra::quadratics"
    "difficulty":  string  - "easy" | "medium" | "hard"
    "source":      string  - origin URL / dataset / "GMATWiz original (authored)"
    "license":     string  - see Section 5 (never claims a license we can't verify)
    "scraped_at":  string  - ISO-8601 UTC timestamp
  }

Topic taxonomy (18 leaves, PRD Section 5):
  Arithmetic: number_properties, fractions, decimals, percents,
              ratios_proportions, exponents_roots, statistics, sets, counting,
              probability
  Algebra:    linear_equations, quadratics, inequalities, absolute_value,
              functions, sequences, expressions, word_problems


-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
3. SOURCES ATTEMPTED (and their outcomes)
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Three source adapters were attempted. robots.txt was respected by default.

(1) GMAT Club - free "Problem Solving (PS)" forum  [BLOCKED]
    Site:        https://gmatclub.com
    Entry point: https://gmatclub.com/forum/problem-solving-ps-140/
    robots.txt:  Request for /robots.txt returned HTTP 403 (Cloudflare bot
                 protection). Per our conservative policy an inaccessible
                 robots.txt is treated as "Disallow: /".
    Result:      0 items. Skipped to respect robots / access controls.
    License plan if ever ingested: "scraped-unverified" (forum content;
                 copyright retained by the original posters - it would be
                 quarantined and kept OUT of any redistributable pool).

(2) Reddit r/GMAT - public listing/search JSON  [BLOCKED]
    Site:        https://www.reddit.com/r/GMAT
    Entry point: https://www.reddit.com/r/GMAT/search.json?q=problem+solving
    robots.txt:  Explicit "User-agent: *  Disallow: /" (Reddit Public Content
                 Policy). We respected it and did not crawl.
    Result:      0 items. (Reddit also blocks unauthenticated bots at the HTTP
                 layer; the compliant route is the official Reddit Data API with
                 OAuth, which is out of scope for this offline pipeline.)
    License plan if ever ingested: "scraped-unverified" (user posts).

(3) AQuA-RAT (DeepMind) - open dataset  [OK - 231 items]
    Site:        https://github.com/google-deepmind/AQuA
    Fetched:     https://raw.githubusercontent.com/google-deepmind/AQuA/master/test.json
    robots.txt:  No blocking robots rule for the raw content host; allowed.
    License:     Apache-2.0 (VERIFIED open + redistributable with attribution).
    Format:      JSON-lines; each line has question, 5 options (A-E), a rationale,
                 and the correct letter - i.e. native GMAT/GRE-style Problem
                 Solving multiple choice. Ideal for normalization.
    Raw fetched: 254 questions.
    Dropped:     16 out-of-scope (geometry)  +  7 duplicate-option items
                 = 23 dropped, per the PRD scope filter and a quality filter.
    Normalized:  231 in-scope questions kept (after dedupe: 0 further removed).
    Citation:    Ling, Yogatama, Dyer, Blunsom (2017), "Program Induction by
                 Rationale Generation: Learning to Solve and Explain Algebraic
                 Word Problems," ACL 2017.

SUMMARY (counts scraped per source):
    gmatclub : 0   (blocked - robots.txt 403 / Cloudflare)
    reddit   : 0   (blocked - robots.txt Disallow: /)
    aqua_rat : 231 (Apache-2.0, open)
    -----------------------------------
    TOTAL scraped & normalized: 231


